I never had a period until I was almost 16 and even then, there was nothing normal about what I felt.

More than 10 years ago - I found out I had PCOS. 

3 years ago - I had to stop jogging, running, walking, and doing much of anything physically because it all caused extreme pain in my uterus and the pain would radiate. 

It got so bad, I needed to see a doc (I thought it was normal until about 3 years ago). Birth control for a year - made it worse.

I has an excision surgery in Nov 2019 and she told me there wasn't much. 

I had a hysterectomy 5 weeks ago and he said he removed a lot of endo, esp around my right ovary and showed me my PCOS. 

Before my hysterectomy,  I experienced pain every. single. day.  My uterus was the primary source of my pain.  I could feel it.  It felt like my uterus was constantly attacking my body.  My hips hurt soooo freaking bad, there were days I literally couldn't pick up my right leg to walk to the restroom.  It hurt down into my legs so bad.  Down to my knees.  My back.  The pain caused so much fatigue and crying.  I ended up on an anti depressant (started taking it a year ago) (so I could stop crying from all the pain). The pain was so constant.... so freaking constant... bowl issues.  There was never enough heat on my back and on my lower abdomen.  It was never hot enough!!!! I could have burn marks and it still was not hot enough.. 

These past 5 weeks.... since my hysterectomy... AMAZING (not perfect, but so much freaking better)!! I will take surgical pain every day for the rest of my life if that means I dont have to experience that endo/pcos again.  I can't begin to describe it.  I know a hysterectomy isn't a cure... but it worked for me, my emotions, and my body.

I know I'm still healing and I promise I'm listening to my body!! I can not begin to tell you all the ways I feel so much better!!! I even have been taking short (leisurely) walks!!

